arXiv.abstract:
The Fock-Bargmann-Hartogs domain $D_{n,m}(\mu)$ ($\mu>0$) in $\mathbb{C}^{n+m}$ is defined by the inequality $\|w\|^2<e^{-\mu\|z\|^2},$ where $(z,w)\in \mathbb{C}^n	imes \mathbb{C}^m$, which is an unbounded non-hyperbolic domain in $\mathbb{C}^{n+m}$. This paper introduces a K"{a}hler metric $\alpha g(\mu;
u)$ $(\alpha>0)$ on $D_{n,m}(\mu)$, where $g(\mu;
u)$ is the K"{a}hler metric associated with the K"{a}hler potential $\Phi(z,w):=\mu
u{\Vert z\Vert}^{2}-\ln(e^{-\mu{\Vert z\Vert}^{2}}-\Vert w\Vert^2)$ ($
u>-1$) on $D_{n,m}(\mu)$. The purpose of this paper is twofold. Firstly, we obtain an explicit formula for the Bergman kernel of the weighted Hilbert space of square integrable holomorphic functions on $(D_{n,m}(\mu), g(\mu;
u))$ with the weight $\exp\{-\alpha \Phi\}$ for $\alpha>0$. Secondly, using the explicit expression of the Bergman kernel, we obtain the necessary and sufficient condition for the metric $\alpha g(\mu;
u)$ $(\alpha>0)$ on the domain $D_{n,m}(\mu)$ to be a balanced metric. So we obtain the existence of balanced metrics for a class of Fock-Bargmann-Hartogs domains.

  This paper presents a proof of the following conjecture, stated by Nishizawa
in [Appl. Math. Comput. 269, (2015), 146--154.]: for $\displaystyle 0<x<\pi/2$
the inequality $ \displaystyle \frac{\sin{x}}{x} \!>\! \left(\frac{2}{\pi} +
\frac{\pi\!-\!2}{\pi^{3}}(\pi^{2}\!-\!4x^{2})\right)^{\theta(x)}\! $ holds,
where $\displaystyle \theta(x) \! = \! -\frac{(48\!-\!24\pi\!+\!\pi^{3})x^{3}
}{3(\pi\!-\!2)\pi^{3}}+\frac{\pi^{3}}{24(\pi\!-\!2)}.$

In the framework of the minimal $U(1)_{B-L}$ extension of the Standard Model, we investigate the Higgs boson production processes $e^{+}e^{-}ightarrow ZH$, $e^{+}e^{-}ightarrow 
u_{e} ar{
u_{e}}H$, $e^{+}e^{-}ightarrow t ar{t}H$, $e^{+}e^{-}ightarrow ZHH$ and $e^{+}e^{-}ightarrow 
u_{e} ar{
u_{e}}HH$ at the International Linear Collider (ILC). We present the production cross sections, the relative corrections and compare our results with the expected experimental accuracies for Higgs decay channel $Hightarrow b ar{b}$. In the allowed parameter space, we find that the effects of the three single Higgs boson production processes might approach the observable threshold of the ILC, and that the Higgs signal strengths $\mu_{b ar{b}}$ of the two double Higgs boson production processes are all out of the observable threshold of the ILC so that the effects will be difficult to be observed at the ILC.
